{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"32232b3c-8b0b-4105-935d-eebbd6c44086","content":"Here's the skip attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute | Example |\n|-----------|-----------|---------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` | `[TestMethod, Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` | `[Fact(Skip = \"Blocked by bug #123\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` | `[Test, Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` | `[Test, Skip(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]` |\n\n**Notes:**\n- **xUnit `[Theory]`** also supports `Skip`: `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]`\n- **MSTest & NUnit** `[Ignore]` requires a reason string.\n- All four will report the test as **skipped** (not failed) in test results, preserving the reason message.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f6af37d6-2223-4c6d-b762-eb7dc72d0892","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the correct skip/ignore attributes for MSTest, xUnit, NUnit, and TUnit test frameworks. This is a knowledge question about .NET test frameworks. Let me check if the `dotnet-test-frameworks` skill has relevant information, as it's described as \"Reference data for .NET test framework detection patterns, assertion APIs, skip annotations, setup/teardown methods.\"","outputTokens":337,"requestId":"0C07:29D6CF:549D6F:62C712:69F00970"},"id":"4870cea7-3759-4062-82d0-6a545a3ca027","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:12:24.739Z","parentId":"80a45be2-6372-466b-8a1b-d6f936bb078b"}
